WEBVTT

00:02.728 --> 00:04.837
♪ ♪

00:05.064 --> 00:07.172
(school bell rings)

00:09.193 --> 00:10.417
"Then Papa Bear said,

00:10.511 --> 00:13.086
'Someone's been sleeping
in my bed.'"

00:13.239 --> 00:15.255
This book is so unrealistic.

00:15.407 --> 00:19.243
Dads sleep on the weight bench
in the garage, right?

00:19.245 --> 00:21.595
Okay, Riley, ready to do this?

00:22.598 --> 00:25.173
Tell you what,
you just hang out in there

00:25.192 --> 00:27.251
while I read, okay?

00:27.269 --> 00:29.511
Oh, this dumb book.

00:29.605 --> 00:33.607
"Every day, the milkman brings
fresh milk to your milk box."

00:34.760 --> 00:38.353
But... the milkman
has to be real careful,

00:38.447 --> 00:41.098
because hiding inside
every milk box is...

00:41.191 --> 00:43.767
a fart monster!

00:43.786 --> 00:45.693
(mimics flatulence)

00:45.713 --> 00:47.212
Does it really say that?

00:47.364 --> 00:51.050
Sit back, kid, and I'll tell you
where milk really comes from.

00:52.111 --> 00:54.795
On the farm,
cows eat pig boogers...

00:54.889 --> 00:56.204
Moo!

00:56.223 --> 00:58.465
BART:
...which their butts
turn into milk.

00:58.617 --> 01:01.952
Then the cows
are loaded onto farm rockets.

01:01.970 --> 01:03.878
(mooing)

01:03.898 --> 01:06.565
(cackles)

01:06.792 --> 01:08.292
BART:
But space goats
and astro donkeys

01:08.310 --> 01:10.811
headbutt the beef shuttle!

01:10.963 --> 01:14.364
And that
is where milk comes from.

01:16.468 --> 01:18.135
(laughing)

01:18.228 --> 01:20.654
I thought drawing in books
wasn't allowed.

01:20.748 --> 01:22.414
Hey, who's the big kid here?

01:22.566 --> 01:24.249
You are.

01:31.500 --> 01:32.649
(gulps)

01:32.668 --> 01:34.576
Thanks to your little prank,

01:34.595 --> 01:37.912
-25 library books were ruined.
-(sighs)

01:37.932 --> 01:41.007
Haven't we told you
that books are precious?

01:41.102 --> 01:43.827
I'm afraid to count
how many times I've said that.

01:43.846 --> 01:44.937
No, you weren't even there.

01:45.106 --> 01:47.164
I was just trying
to make it fun for the kid.

01:47.182 --> 01:48.590
You never take my side.

01:48.609 --> 01:51.944
Side? Get a load of this kid
with a side.

01:52.095 --> 01:53.946
How dare you defend yourself?

01:54.097 --> 01:56.006
You are the destroyer!

01:56.024 --> 01:57.432
Yes, that's it.

01:57.526 --> 01:58.692
The destroyer.

01:58.786 --> 01:59.860
You ruin everything,

01:59.954 --> 02:02.195
even our holiday picture.

02:02.289 --> 02:05.940
HOMER:
There's no such thing
as Christmas fangs!

02:06.034 --> 02:09.536
I had to wear a scarf
to midnight mass.

02:09.630 --> 02:11.797
I don't have a moment
when I'm not worried

02:11.948 --> 02:13.540
about what you'll do next.

02:13.692 --> 02:15.375
I can't... I ju...

02:15.469 --> 02:16.693
(panting)

02:16.786 --> 02:17.711
I can't...

02:17.863 --> 02:19.363
Babe, babe, tag me in.

02:19.365 --> 02:21.531
I can take him.
Destroyer.

02:21.625 --> 02:24.551
Our house is filled
with unexploded pranks.

02:24.703 --> 02:28.463
Any toilet seat
could be covered in superglue.

02:28.557 --> 02:30.131
Bart put hot dog water
in the ice maker.

02:30.151 --> 02:31.984
He's the destroyer!

02:32.135 --> 02:33.710
I just told him that.

02:33.803 --> 02:35.195
Good.

02:36.657 --> 02:39.065
Ten years as your father
has left me empty.

02:39.218 --> 02:41.476
Like an orange soda bottle
at a picnic--

02:41.495 --> 02:44.646
sticky and covered
with dying bees!

02:44.665 --> 02:45.813
I'm just...

02:45.833 --> 02:47.891
I c... I can't...

02:47.910 --> 02:49.168
Babe, babe.

02:49.395 --> 02:50.335
Okay, punishments.

02:50.487 --> 02:52.153
What's your
least favorite vegetable?

02:52.173 --> 02:53.321
Swiss chard.
(gasps)

02:53.415 --> 02:55.565
You're looking at a whole lot

02:55.584 --> 02:58.159
of swiss chard
sandwiches, buster.

02:58.179 --> 03:01.388
And you're never allowed
to read a book again!

03:02.499 --> 03:05.091
Okay, first off,
we're on your side.

03:05.244 --> 03:07.911
What Bart did was inexcusable.

03:07.930 --> 03:09.855
He's a bad kid.
Straight up.

03:10.006 --> 03:12.173
You're lucky you only
have him for one year.

03:12.267 --> 03:13.675
Well, it might be two,

03:13.769 --> 03:15.510
but that's another meeting.

03:15.529 --> 03:17.103
But don't you worry.

03:17.198 --> 03:20.348
The unholy parade of punishments
we've cooked up for Bart

03:20.367 --> 03:22.201
is both cruel and unusual.

03:22.352 --> 03:24.277
When he opens his eyes
every morning,

03:24.430 --> 03:26.096
his first thought will be,

03:26.265 --> 03:28.189
"Oh, no, another day."

03:28.283 --> 03:31.192
Before we explore
the punishment space,

03:31.212 --> 03:33.212
let me show you something.

03:35.198 --> 03:37.090
I love books now.

03:37.200 --> 03:40.052
(excited chatter)

03:40.203 --> 03:42.112
Oh, the kids haven't been
this excited to read

03:42.130 --> 03:45.873
since we accidentally stocked
Matthew Perry's autobiography.

03:45.893 --> 03:47.226
All thanks to your son.

03:47.453 --> 03:50.303
Bart was just trying
to help his younger peers

03:50.456 --> 03:52.714
engage with their
reading interactively--

03:52.733 --> 03:54.291
"make it fun."

03:54.309 --> 03:55.976
Well, he said that to us, too,

03:56.128 --> 03:58.128
but we didn't believe him.

03:58.146 --> 04:00.072
We've sort of learned
never to believe him.

04:00.241 --> 04:01.907
"One evening, Ralph decided

04:02.134 --> 04:04.559
to go for a walk
in the moonlight."

04:04.578 --> 04:08.154
This is the first book he hasn't
tried to kiss or wear as a hat.

04:08.249 --> 04:11.899
Oh, Bart is such
a wonderful, amazing son.

04:12.068 --> 04:14.068
That's always been our feeling.

04:14.088 --> 04:17.572
May I hug the people
who created Bart?

04:17.591 --> 04:19.758
Mmm, mmm, ooh.

04:19.985 --> 04:22.594
What just happened in there?

04:22.763 --> 04:24.263
Bart? Good?

04:24.490 --> 04:26.581
Nothing makes sense anymore.

04:26.600 --> 04:30.060
I-I don't-I don't think
this is our car.

04:31.013 --> 04:32.996
What color is our car, Marge?

04:33.015 --> 04:34.106
Black? Uh...

04:34.257 --> 04:36.516
No, no, no,
that's-that's not it.

04:36.668 --> 04:39.352
How is it everyone else
saw the best in Bart

04:39.521 --> 04:40.687
and we didn't?

04:40.839 --> 04:43.765
Are we horrible parents?

04:43.842 --> 04:47.027
I don't know. I-I mean,
we love Bart, don't we?

04:47.195 --> 04:49.437
Oh, so much.

04:49.531 --> 04:50.697
So much.

04:50.849 --> 04:54.668
But what if we don't
like him?

04:59.875 --> 05:02.208
We don't like our own son!

05:02.361 --> 05:04.528
We're horrible parents.

05:04.621 --> 05:05.787
It's not our fault.

05:05.806 --> 05:07.622
He just wears you down.

05:07.716 --> 05:09.049
I can't take it.

05:09.201 --> 05:11.568
And I'm the strongest person
I know.

05:11.628 --> 05:15.055
We weren't planning on starting
a family when we had him.

05:15.207 --> 05:16.631
What if, deep down,

05:16.725 --> 05:19.526
we blame Bart for throwing
our lives out of whack?

05:19.636 --> 05:21.878
That's the thing
no one ever tells you:

05:21.897 --> 05:24.881
having kids changes your life.

05:24.900 --> 05:27.067
I just wish so much

05:27.161 --> 05:29.386
that we could see him
like other people do,

05:29.404 --> 05:33.648
without all the emotional gunk
of ten years of parenting him.

05:33.742 --> 05:35.483
He deserves that much.

05:35.502 --> 05:38.912
Maybe.
But that's not how life works.

05:39.006 --> 05:40.714
(thunder rumbles)

05:41.900 --> 05:44.134
It just doesn't.

05:49.074 --> 05:51.725
-(yawns)
-Mm...

05:52.911 --> 05:55.670
Another beautiful day.

05:55.689 --> 05:57.247
Should we go wake the kids?

05:57.340 --> 05:58.023
Sure.

05:58.174 --> 06:01.026
Why don't we each take one?

06:01.177 --> 06:03.010
Two parents, two kids--

06:03.030 --> 06:04.938
the perfect family.

06:05.090 --> 06:07.366
♪ ♪

06:13.207 --> 06:15.332
("Morgenblätter, Op. 279"
by Strauss playing)

06:37.547 --> 06:40.399
♪ ♪

06:56.250 --> 06:58.250
♪ ♪

07:02.481 --> 07:04.363
So what are we looking at today?

07:04.516 --> 07:07.317
Well, I heard Dr. Vargas
is cheating on Dr. Chen

07:07.335 --> 07:09.243
with that gorgeous new resident.

07:09.337 --> 07:11.579
Great.
Now, what about our patients?

07:11.598 --> 07:14.766
I have no idea. But I made
a chart showing who on staff

07:14.918 --> 07:16.009
is hooking up with who.

07:16.103 --> 07:17.936
What is it
about big-city hospitals

07:18.087 --> 07:19.846
that attracts
the most melodramatic,

07:19.940 --> 07:22.499
sex-obsessed health workers
on Earth?

07:22.517 --> 07:24.526
(indistinct chatter)

07:31.768 --> 07:34.936
Dr. Simpson. They need you
in Room 6. Code Blue!

07:34.955 --> 07:36.938
-What's the crisis?
-Dr. Kern fell in love

07:37.073 --> 07:38.123
with his wife's sister's wife,

07:38.200 --> 07:40.333
and now he's questioning
everything.

07:41.444 --> 07:42.777
(groans)

07:42.871 --> 07:44.037
(beeping)

07:44.189 --> 07:45.188
Break's over.

07:45.323 --> 07:47.207
<i> ("Charge" fanfare plays)</i>

07:47.359 --> 07:49.092
<i> CROWD:</i>
<i> Charge!</i>

07:49.970 --> 07:52.712
HOMER:
I love my job.

07:52.864 --> 07:55.031
Okay, Homer,
bottom of the ninth.

07:55.050 --> 07:57.884
Let's get this stadium rocking.

07:58.036 --> 08:00.103
(grunting gently)

08:02.390 --> 08:04.191
♪ ♪

08:05.043 --> 08:06.651
(crowd cheering)

08:06.803 --> 08:07.727
HOMER:
Fifty?

08:07.879 --> 08:09.321
You can do better than that.

08:10.716 --> 08:12.365
(exclaims)

08:15.662 --> 08:17.570
We're almost at maximum noise.

08:17.664 --> 08:19.055
Maybe today's the day.

08:19.074 --> 08:20.999
Release the rally ferret!

08:22.193 --> 08:24.077
♪<i> Insane in the membrane</i> ♪

08:24.229 --> 08:26.296
♪<i> Insane in the brain</i> ♪

08:31.586 --> 08:32.736
(sighs)

08:32.829 --> 08:33.903
Maybe, in the end,

08:33.922 --> 08:37.224
mankind wasn't meant
to be 100 loud.

08:38.093 --> 08:40.018
Ah.
Well, that's my daily

08:40.169 --> 08:41.578
eight ounces of light beer.

08:41.596 --> 08:44.581
Thirst quenched,
I'll head directly home.

08:44.599 --> 08:47.767
Just once, I'd like to see
Homer Simpson get drunk.

08:47.861 --> 08:48.843
Ah, well.

08:48.862 --> 08:50.195
(vuvuzela blares)

08:52.107 --> 08:54.090
Uh-oh, better tap a new keg

08:54.109 --> 08:56.368
for the happiest man
in Springfield.

08:56.595 --> 08:58.928
Yeah, what's your secret,
Skin-man?

08:58.989 --> 09:00.780
Eh, a stimulating job
at a school

09:00.874 --> 09:02.098
full of obedient children,

09:02.191 --> 09:04.284
with not one
troublemaker in the bunch.

09:04.360 --> 09:06.770
Not a one.

09:06.788 --> 09:09.789
I'm all the trouble he needs.

09:09.883 --> 09:11.049
Well, I'm off.

09:11.200 --> 09:13.301
See you later, wild man.

09:15.447 --> 09:16.721
("Lido Shuffle" by Boz Scaggs
starts playing)

09:16.873 --> 09:18.431
♪<i> Lido</i> ♪

09:19.709 --> 09:21.726
♪<i> Whoa...</i> ♪

09:24.790 --> 09:26.047
You guys are so sweet,

09:26.215 --> 09:28.808
surprising me with
ice cream after work.

09:28.960 --> 09:30.627
It was Lisa's idea.

09:30.720 --> 09:34.314
Well, Ice Cream Parlor
Malibu Stacy wanted some, too.

09:34.390 --> 09:37.450
(whoops) Ice cream party!

09:38.245 --> 09:40.561
Oh, no. Oh, no. Oh, no.

09:40.581 --> 09:42.414
Oh, no.

09:42.641 --> 09:44.541
(gasping)

09:45.644 --> 09:47.502
Oh, no!

09:49.572 --> 09:50.980
MARGE:
It's a child.

09:50.999 --> 09:52.482
(groans)

09:52.575 --> 09:54.092
Homer, he's alive.

09:56.988 --> 09:58.655
Who are you, little boy?

09:58.657 --> 10:01.507
Where are your parents?
What's your name?

10:01.602 --> 10:03.827
I'm Bart... um, something.

10:03.920 --> 10:05.186
Who the hell are you?

10:06.832 --> 10:08.940
Now, you can't remember anything

10:09.109 --> 10:10.591
before the accident?

10:10.611 --> 10:11.926
Sorry, I got nothing.

10:12.095 --> 10:13.837
Well, have you ever
had amnesia before?

10:13.930 --> 10:15.596
No way I'd forget
something like that.

10:15.765 --> 10:18.174
Well, until we figure out
who this kid is,

10:18.193 --> 10:19.859
I'm gonna have to keep him
down at the station.

10:20.011 --> 10:22.345
Hey, uh, are you
a true crime buff?

10:22.364 --> 10:25.198
Hope so, 'cause you're sleeping
one cell over from this guy

10:25.350 --> 10:27.942
who is gonna be huge
on<i> Dateline.</i>

10:27.961 --> 10:29.777
No, don't take him to jail.

10:29.796 --> 10:31.871
He can stay at our house.

10:32.023 --> 10:34.782
The poor thing.
He must be so scared.

10:34.876 --> 10:37.636
X-ray of my butt for you.
One for you.

10:37.787 --> 10:39.763
Two for the lady.

10:40.974 --> 10:43.216
Aw, nice pile of bricks
you got here.

10:43.368 --> 10:45.034
So, what's your deal?
I thought rich people

10:45.128 --> 10:47.036
were supposed to be skinny.

10:47.130 --> 10:48.388
We're not rich.

10:48.464 --> 10:49.814
It's just that Marge and I both

10:49.966 --> 10:51.557
have great jobs that we love.

10:51.710 --> 10:53.393
(yawns)

10:53.487 --> 10:57.213
Everything you see here
is a result of careful planning.

10:57.232 --> 10:59.324
(imitates snoring)

11:01.219 --> 11:04.812
Is he fake-snoring so as
to imply that we're boring?

11:04.831 --> 11:06.331
I think he is.

11:06.558 --> 11:09.501
Well, let's see how he likes
a taste of his own medicine.

11:09.728 --> 11:11.461
(imitates snoring)

11:12.731 --> 11:14.414
(snoring)

11:14.508 --> 11:15.674
Ah, my medicine.

11:17.827 --> 11:19.344
Can we both admit I won this?

11:19.495 --> 11:22.830
(sighs)
I'll take you to your room.

11:22.924 --> 11:23.907
What are you waiting for?

11:23.925 --> 11:26.101
This ain't over anytime soon.

11:27.762 --> 11:30.930
Aw, the cheap bed in my room
broke for some reason.

11:31.082 --> 11:32.506
What you got going on in here?

11:32.526 --> 11:35.694
Malibu Stacy is going on
a shopping trip to the mall.

11:35.921 --> 11:37.178
So fun.

11:37.197 --> 11:39.030
Why don't you take them
out of their boxes?

11:39.182 --> 11:40.924
Then you can
smash them with a rock,

11:40.942 --> 11:42.442
light their hair on fire.

11:42.536 --> 11:43.426
Lot of good options.

11:43.445 --> 11:45.094
If I take them out of the box,

11:45.096 --> 11:46.779
they won't be perfect anymore.

11:46.915 --> 11:49.741
Uh, I might have a little OCD.

11:49.893 --> 11:52.293
ADHD.
Nice to meet you.

11:55.364 --> 11:58.007
("Morgenblätter, Op. 279"
by Strauss playing)

12:09.563 --> 12:12.147
♪ ♪

12:16.236 --> 12:17.977
-♪<i> Lido...</i> ♪
-Mmm, nothing like
a morning drive

12:18.129 --> 12:21.406
with the top down.
Got Boz Scaggs on the radio.

12:21.557 --> 12:23.316
Life is tight.

12:23.392 --> 12:24.968
(gasps)

12:25.061 --> 12:26.986
-(squish)
-(tires screech)
-(crash)

12:27.063 --> 12:28.580
My cool-- it's gone!

12:28.807 --> 12:31.249
MISS SPRINGFIELD:
Goodbye, Seymour.

12:33.328 --> 12:34.735
(humming)

12:34.755 --> 12:36.588
(giggling)

12:37.832 --> 12:40.675
No, Maggie.
Bubble boy bad.

12:42.003 --> 12:44.262
Where's Mom?
I have to make my own sandwich

12:44.372 --> 12:46.598
and write my own
sweet note to myself

12:46.825 --> 12:48.749
on my lunch bag?
I mean, co...

12:48.843 --> 12:50.343
Ugh.
All right, um...

12:50.495 --> 12:54.180
"The world will be great today
because you are."

12:54.332 --> 12:56.090
Aw, that's sweet.

12:56.184 --> 12:59.444
And here's an inspirational
quote from Uncle Bart.

13:01.597 --> 13:03.006
"Eat my shorts."

13:03.099 --> 13:04.507
Oh, very clever.

13:04.600 --> 13:06.526
If someone actually
ate your shorts,

13:06.620 --> 13:07.860
what would it mean?

13:08.013 --> 13:09.695
I don't know, just
something you say so people

13:09.848 --> 13:11.438
don't mess with you,
because you're the boss

13:11.458 --> 13:14.441
and if they don't like it,
they can eat your shorts.

13:14.536 --> 13:17.537
So, did you remember
where home is yet,

13:17.631 --> 13:19.872
low-maintenance guest?

13:19.966 --> 13:21.782
Sorry, guys,
I know as much about me

13:21.876 --> 13:23.209
as you know about me,

13:23.378 --> 13:24.385
which is...

13:25.288 --> 13:27.955
-(belching): I rule.
-(barks)

13:27.974 --> 13:29.808
Aw, we're all breathing that.

13:29.976 --> 13:32.101
(belching)

13:33.204 --> 13:35.146
I know he's just
a stray kid in need,

13:35.298 --> 13:37.223
but I don't like him.

13:37.375 --> 13:39.609
I'm gonna play
a little pickleball.

13:41.804 --> 13:44.805
-(grunting)
-I bet his parents
don't even like him.

13:44.825 --> 13:46.741
I mean, who could?

13:47.661 --> 13:50.078
-(gasps)
-(growls)

13:54.742 --> 13:56.150
-♪ ♪
-(crowd cheering)

13:56.244 --> 13:57.836
For a guy who sweats
when he thinks,

13:57.987 --> 13:59.320
you've got a pretty sweet gig.

13:59.339 --> 14:01.506
Listen up, Memento Junior,

14:01.657 --> 14:03.675
just because I don't
want you alone in my home

14:03.826 --> 14:05.176
doesn't mean I want you here.

14:05.369 --> 14:08.680
Wow, thousands of drunk dads
and their bored kids

14:08.831 --> 14:10.073
under your total control.

14:10.241 --> 14:11.757
You can make them
do anything you want.

14:11.852 --> 14:13.167
Well, not anything.

14:13.186 --> 14:15.595
Actually, there are pretty
strict rules about...

14:15.689 --> 14:17.063
Hey, stop that!

14:21.027 --> 14:22.768
What have you done?

14:22.863 --> 14:24.571
(cheering)

14:28.443 --> 14:31.944
(gasps)
95? What have you done?

14:32.097 --> 14:33.997
And by all means, do more.

14:50.115 --> 14:51.948
Oh, my God.

14:52.117 --> 14:53.641
Can this be happening?

14:58.398 --> 15:00.881
A hundred!
I finally got 100!

15:00.901 --> 15:03.401
It's the most noise
there can ever be.

15:03.552 --> 15:05.719
(crowd cheering)

15:05.739 --> 15:08.222
Kid, I don't know who you are
or where you came from,

15:08.241 --> 15:10.074
but you made magic today.

15:10.226 --> 15:11.910
You showed this
set-in-his-ways

15:12.061 --> 15:13.970
old Jumbotron operator

15:14.063 --> 15:16.139
that there's a beautiful chaos
in this job

15:16.157 --> 15:18.399
I never dreamed existed.

15:18.567 --> 15:20.251
You're all right.

15:20.478 --> 15:22.420
And you're easily won over.

15:22.571 --> 15:25.924
<i> (The Simpsons</i> theme
plays on organ)

15:27.284 --> 15:30.336
Kid turns our house
upside down in one night.

15:30.430 --> 15:31.654
Who the hell am I?

15:31.673 --> 15:33.005
Who the hell are you?

15:33.099 --> 15:34.098
Oh, my God, have you heard?

15:34.250 --> 15:35.916
The man we
thought was Dr. Taylor

15:36.010 --> 15:38.344
was actually his murderous twin.

15:38.496 --> 15:40.680
And last night, he proposed!

15:40.774 --> 15:42.665
Not today, Tracey.

15:42.834 --> 15:44.392
(barking, meowing)

15:45.428 --> 15:47.428
Why are we not
treating any patients?

15:47.447 --> 15:48.929
Where's my staff?

15:48.949 --> 15:50.114
Who's ready to find out

15:50.341 --> 15:52.266
which of my
three co-worker lovers

15:52.285 --> 15:54.343
is the father of my child?

15:54.362 --> 15:56.454
(whooping)

15:56.605 --> 15:58.439
Enough!

15:58.959 --> 16:01.275
No more romance.
No more intrigue.

16:01.369 --> 16:03.369
The next person who does
anything dramatic is fired.

16:03.521 --> 16:05.463
And if you don't
like it, you can

16:05.690 --> 16:07.614
eat my shorts!

16:07.634 --> 16:08.949
(all gasp)

16:08.969 --> 16:10.635
We'll be much more
professional, ma'am.

16:10.786 --> 16:12.862
Maybe the sex closet

16:12.880 --> 16:14.380
could be a supply closet?

16:14.532 --> 16:17.033
And the sex-mobile
could be an ambulance.

16:17.051 --> 16:18.701
"Eat my shorts."

16:18.720 --> 16:22.563
Still don't know what it means,
but it really works.

16:24.467 --> 16:25.966
Hey, Jitters.
What you working on?

16:26.060 --> 16:27.376
I'm doing a diorama

16:27.395 --> 16:29.562
on the history of homework.

16:29.656 --> 16:32.215
Did you know that
in ancient Assyria,

16:32.308 --> 16:34.141
novice scribes had to get...

16:34.160 --> 16:36.402
Oh, it's Friday, nerd.

16:36.554 --> 16:38.571
Put down the tweezers
and live a little.

16:38.647 --> 16:40.314
W-wait, let me just
finish the detailing

16:40.333 --> 16:42.391
on this Trapper Keeper
because then I...

16:42.485 --> 16:44.168
When I need to relax,
I like to watch

16:44.395 --> 16:45.745
a little<i> Itchy and Scratchy.</i>

16:45.839 --> 16:47.413
Yeah, I've seen the lunch boxes.

16:47.565 --> 16:48.414
It's not for me.

16:48.566 --> 16:49.674
You'll love it.

16:49.751 --> 16:50.733
It's about a cat and a mouse

16:50.752 --> 16:51.901
trying to kill each other.

16:51.994 --> 16:54.328
You know-- the human experience.

16:54.405 --> 16:57.432
